commit_message: Add brotli decompressorThis commit is for the decoder for brotli compression format.nBrotli is a generic byte-level compression algorithm.n
Fix name collisions with libwebp.Prefix all externally visible function names with Brotli andnmake all other functions static.n
Make the brotli decoder more C90-compatible.(1) Move all variable declarations to the beginning of the block.n(2) Remove 'z' printf modifiers.n(3) Fix 'comma at the end of enumeration list' warning.n
Add brotli compressorThis commit is for the encoder for brotli compression format.nBrotli is a generic byte-level compression algorithm.n

Updates to Brotli compression format, decoder and encoderThis commit contains a batch of changes that were made to the Brotlincompression algorithm in the last three weeks. Most important changes:nn  * Added UTF8 context model for good text compression.n  * Simplified context modeling by having only 4 context modes.n  * Per-block context mode selection.n  * Faster backward copying and bit reading functions.n  * More efficient histogram coding.n  * Streaming support for the decoder and encoder.n
Added Brotli compress/decompress utilities and makefiles
Add draft specification of the brotli format

Updates to Brotli compression format, decoder and encoderThis commit contains a batch of changes that were made to the Brotlincompression algorithm in the last month. Most important changes:nn   * Updated specn   * Changed Huffman code length alphabet to use run length codes moren efficiently, based on a suggestion by Robert Obrykn   * Changed encoding of the number of Huffman code lengths (HLEN)n   * Changed encoding of the number of Huffman trees (NTREES)n   * Added support for uncompressed meta-blocksn

Brotli format change: improved encoding of Huffman codesThis change removes the redundant HCLEN, HLENINC and HLENnfields from the encoding of the complex Huffman codes andnderives these from an invariant of the code length sequence.nBased on a patch by Robert Obryk.n
Bug fixes for the brotli encoder and decoder.
Small update to brotli specification.Clarify how to recover from error conditions caused by overflowingnblock types and symbol values.n
Brotli format change: small improvement to the encoding of Huffman codesCombine the HSKIP and the simple/complex Huffman code type bits.n
Fix -Wconversion compiler warnings in the brotli decoder.

Updates to Brotli compression format, decoder and encoderThis commit contains a batch of changes that were made to the Brotlincompression algorithm in the last month. Most important changes:nn   * Fixes to the spec.n   * Change of code length code order.n   * Use a 2-level Huffman lookup table in the decoder.n   * Faster uncompressed meta-block decoding.n   * Optimized encoding of the Huffman code.n   * Detection of UTF-8 input encoding.n   * UTF-8 based literal cost modeling for improvedn backward reference selection.n

Updates to Brotli compression format, decoder and encoderThis commit contains a batch of changes that were made to the Brotlincompression algorithm in the last month. Most important changes:nn   * Format change: don't push distances representing static dictionary words to the distance cache.n   * Fix decoder invalid memory access bug caused by building a non-complete Huffman tree.n   * Add a mode parameter to the encoder interface.n   * Use different hashers for text and font mode.n   * Add a heuristics to the hasher for skipping non-compressible data.n   * Exhaustive search of static dictionary during backward reference search.n

Add Mark Adler's edits to the specification.The specification source is changed in this commitnto exactly mirror the specification edited by Mark Adler:nnhttps://github.com/madler/brotli/blob/master/brotli-02-edit.nroffn(version 70e53d7)n

Change the specification to be less strict in some cases.In the following three cases we allow more choicesnfor the compressor, which can potentially lead tonless compressed bits.nn  (1) Allow brotli streams where the block countsn  do not count down to exactly zero at the endn  of the meta-block. This makes it possiblen  for compressors to sometimes choose a blockn  count which can be represented with less bitsn  than the exact block count.nn  (2) Remove the restriction that prefix coden  descriptions with exactly one non-zeron  length symbol in the code length alphabetn  must have 1 bit depth. This is becausen  bit depth 1 requires the most bits to encode.nn  (3) Allow any copy length value in the lastn  command where the copy part is ignored.n  This makes it possible for a compressorn  to choose a copy length which can ben  represented with the least amount of bits.nnIn addition to the changes above, this commit alsonhas a wording clarification in the overview sectionnwhere the use of the 'context ID' expression isnchanged to be consistent with the rest of thenspecification, i.e. that it is a function of thenlast two literals or the copy length.n
Merge pull request #75 from szabadka/masterChange the specification to be less strict in some cases.

Support empty meta-blocks with optional ignored metadata.This is a partially backward incompatible format change,nthat makes previously valid brotli streams that containnlarger than 16MB meta-blocks invalid.nnThe impact of this should be minimal, since the 'bro'ncommand-line tool does not create larger than 2MBnmeta-blocks, so the only streams this change couldnbreak are those created by a custom brotli encoder.nnThis commit contains only the specification update,nimplementation in the decoder and encoder willnfollow in later commits.n
Merge pull request #76 from szabadka/masterSupport empty meta-blocks with optional ignored metadata.
Decoder support for new empty meta-block format.This change enforces the new 16MB limit on thensize of the meta-blocks and adds support fornempty meta-blocks with optional ignored metadata.n

Speed and memory usage improvements for the decoder.* Change order of members of bit reader state structure.nn* Remove unused includes for assert. Add BROTLI_DCHECKn  macros and use it instead of assert.nn* Do not calculate nbits in common case of ReadSymbol.nn* Introduce and use PREDICT_TRUE / PREDICT_FALSE macros.nn* Allocate less memory in the brotli decoder if it knowsn  the result size beforehand. Before this, the decodern  would always allocate 16MB if the encoder annotated then  window size as 22 bit (which is the default), even if then  file is only a few KB uncompressed. Now, it'll onlyn  allocate a ringbuffer as large as needed for the result file.n  But only if it can know the filesize, it's not possiblen  to know that if there are multiple metablocks or too largen  uncompressed metablock.n

Brotli custom LZ77 dictionary support.Adds functions to prepend such dictionary to thenencoder and decoder, and twiddles their internalnparameters to do as if that was a previous part ofnthe input. This dictionary is just a prefilled LZ77nwindow, it is not related to the built in transformablenbrotli dictionary.n

Bug fixes for the brotli encoder.  * Fix an out-of-bounds access to depth_histo in thenbit cost calculation function.nn  * Change type of distance symbol to uint16_t in blocknsplitter, because if all postfix bits are used, therencan be 520 distance symbols.nn  * Save the distance cache between meta-blocks at thencorrect place. This fixes a roundtrip failure thatncan occur when there is an uncompressed metablocknbetween two compressed metablocks.nn  * Fix a bug when setting lgwin to 24 in the encoder parametersnIt ended up making metablocks larger than 24 bits in size.nn  * Fix out-of-bounds memory accesses in parallel encoder.nCreateBackwardReferences can read up to 4 bytes past end ofninput if the end of input is before mask.nn  * Add missing header for memcpy() in port.hn

Add zopfli-style backward reference search to brotli.This commit adopts the backward reference search algorithmnfrom the zopfli project (see https://github.com/google/zopfli)nto brotli.nnThis slower backward reference search is run only in quality 11nand it runs two iterations of entropy cost modeling andnshortest path search.nnAs a result, the original backward reference search function cannbe simplified a bit, since we can remove some heuristics that werenreplaced with the zopfli-style search.n
Merge pull request #117 from szabadka/masterAdd zopfli-style backward reference search to brotli.

Use a static hash table to look up dictionary words and transforms.This is used for quality 11, for qualities <= 9 we alreadynhave a simpler hash table.nnThe static data size is 252 kB, and this removes thenneed to initialize a huge hash map at startup, which wasnthe reason why transforms had to be disabled by default.nIn comparison, the static dictionary itself is 120 kB.nThis supports every transform, except the kOmitFirstN.n
Merge pull request #118 from szabadka/masterUse a static hash table to look up dictionary words and transforms.

Deprecate greedy_block_split and enable_context_modeling brotli params.These affected only quality 11, and now it does not make sensento disable block splitting or context modeling because most ofnthe time is spent in zopfli anyway.nnNow all speed vs size compromises are controlled by the quality param.n

Use consistent bit ordering and variable namesIf bit-orderings are to be parsed from left-to-right,nthen make the bit-strings left-justified.nIf bit-orderings are to be parsed from right-to-left,nthen make the bit-strings right-justified.nnSection 3.1, which describes how prefix codes worknshows prefix codes that are left-to-right, whichnis better for demonstrating how the work. However,nmost of the rest of the document uses a right-to-leftnconvention. We should distinctly say at the end ofnsection 3.1 that we are switching conventions.nnThus, change the prefix code in section 3.5 to benright-to-left to be consistent with sections 9.1nand 9.2.nnAlso, change the variable names in section 7.3 tonbe consistent with those used in section 10.nnAlso, change the description of MNIBBLES to benMNIBBLES - 4, similar to the convention of sayingnMLEN - 1. Beforehand, the phrasenIf MNIBBLES is 0, then ... was unclear whether itnmeant MNIBBLES before the plus 4 or after.n

This commit makes it so that if you simply do a searchnreplace on these following passages, you get the same thing:nns/NBLTYPESX/(NBLTYPESI|NBLTYPESL|NBLTYPESD)/gns/CATEGORY/(insert-and-copy|literal|distance)/gnn>>>n   1-11 bits: NBLTYPESX, # of CATEGORY block types, encodedn  with the same variable length code as abovenn  Prefix code over the block type code alphabet forn CATEGORY block types, appears only if NBLTYPESX >= 2nn  Prefix code over the block count code alphabet forn CATEGORY block counts, appears only if NBLTYPESX >= 2nn  Block count code + Extra bits for first CATEGORYn block count, appears only if NBLTYPESX >= 2n<<<nn>>>n  Block type code for next CATEGORY block type, appearsn only if NBLTYPESX >= 2 and the previous CATEGORYn block count is zeronn  Block count code + extra bits for next CATEGORYn block count, appears only if NBLTYPESX >= 2 and then previous CATEGORY block count is zeron<<<n

Minor formatting changes* In the description about three categories, explicitly number them insteadnof using a giant paragraph that is harder to follow.nn* Switch lists of items to consistently use American style commas. The Americannstyle lists is better for clarity purposes. Consider the following:nt-Each category of value (insert and copy lengths, literals and distances)nt+Each category of value (insert and copy lengths, literals, and distances)nn* Make sure not to break a hyphenated phrase with a newline. When the nroffnfile is processed, insert-nand-copy becomes insert- and-copy, making itninconsistent with other uses of the hyphenated phrase.nn* Consistently use the same hyphenated phrase if referred to as a single unit.ntinsert and copy   -> insert-and-copyntleast significant -> least-significantntmost significant  -> most-significantntfixed length  -> fixed-lengthntblock switch  -> block-switch.nn* Consistently use indexes instead of indicesn

Clarify simple and complex prefix codes* At the beginning of the simple prefix code section, telling us that a valuenof 1 indicates the number of leading zeros is not very helpful. Instead, itnshould indicate that it means a complex prefix code and point the reader tonthe relevant section (which repeats this information in more detail)nn* Clearly indicate that reusing a value is an error! This seems to be thenbehavior of the of the reference implementation.nn* Clarify what the termination conditions are while reading the prefix codes.nAlso, indicate that it is an error if the prefix tree is over-subscribed ornunder-subscribed.nn* Clearly state what is the maximum number of individual symbols that may benread. This ensures that it is forbidden to an stream that continually says thatnthe symbols have zero length.n

Python: Support streamed compression with the Compressor object (#448)This adds `flush` and `finish` methods to the `Compressor`rnobject in the extension module, renames the `compress` method torn`process`, and updates that method to only process data.  Now,rnone or more `process` calls followed by a `finish` call will bernequivalent to a module-level `compress` call.rnrnNote: To maximize the compression efficiency (and matchrnunderlying Brotli behavior, the `Compressor` object `process`rnmethod does not guarantee all input is immediately written tornoutput. To ensure immediate output, call `flush` to manuallyrnflush the compression buffer.  Extraneous flushing can increasernthe size, but may be required when processing streaming data.rnrnProgress on #191
Python: Publicly expose the Compressor object in the Python API (#456)Progress on #191

Python: Use build instead of build_ext in scripts (#460)Previously, the Python package consisted of a single extensionrnmodule, so `build_ext` was sufficient.  Now, the packagerncontains a native module and an extension module, so bothrn`build_py` and `build_ext` are required.  Instead, run `build`,rnwhich calls both `build_py` and `build_ext` automatically.

Fix missing symbols errors in libbrotlienc and dec (#623)When using autotools to build the binary and libraries, the resulting libraries don't link `brotlicommon` or `m`.rnThis was detected when building cURL 7.57.0 which has now has brotli support. During configure it was failingrn```rnchecking run-time libs availability... failedrnconfigure: error: one or more libs available at link-time are not available run-time. Libs used at link-time: -lbrotlidec -lz -L/usr/local/librn```rninspection of config.log showed missing symbols from libbrotlicommon as the cause.rnrnThis patch results in the encryption and decryption libs to be properly linked against libbrotlicommon and libm.rnSee also https://bugs.freebsd.org/223966

Work around Linuxisms (#627)Missed this in my previous tests. Sorry for that.rnrnOn BSDs, both bc and sed are part of the base operating system. For sed this results in an error as the check construct (--version) is a GNU-ism and only works for GNU sed, not for bsd sed.rnSimilarly, BSD sed does not take parameters after the filename(s) operated on. Moving `-i` to the front fixes that. `-r` is provided for GNU compat in BSD sed as an alias of `-E`. The `-i` option in BSD sed requires an extension to work in-place.rnrn(thank you for picking up the nginx module too!)

Fix brotlidump.py crashing when complex prefix code has exactly 1 non-zero code length (#635)According to the format specification regarding complex prefix codes:rnrn> If there are at least two non-zero code lengths, any trailing zerorn> code lengths are omitted, i.e., the last code length in thern> sequence must be non-zero.  In this case, the sum of (32 >> codern> length) over all the non-zero code lengths must equal to 32.rnrn> If the lengths have been read for the entire code length alphabetrn> and there was only one non-zero code length, then the prefix codern> has one symbol whose code has zero length.rnrnThe script does not handle a case where there is just 1 non-zero codernlength where the sum rule doesn't apply, which causes a StopIterationrnexception when it attempts to read past the list boundaries.rnrnAn example of such file is tests/testdata/mapsdatazrh.compressed. I madernsure this change doesn't break anything by processing all *.compressedrnfiles from the testdata folder with no thrown exceptions.

It combines speed of Sievernand quality of DM. Plus utilities to prepare train corporarn(remove unique strings).rnrnImproved compression ratio: now two sub-blocks could be stitched:rnthe last copy command could be extended to span the next sub-block.rnrnFixed compression ineffectiveness caused by floating numbers rounding andrnwrong cost heuristic.rnrnOther C changes:rn - combined / moved `context.h` to `common`rn - moved transforms to `common`rn - unified some aspects of code formattingrn - added an abstraction for encoder (static) dictionaryrn - moved default allocator/deallocator functions to `common`rnrnbrotli CLI:rn - window size is auto-adjusted if not specified explicitlyrnrnJava:rn - added eager decoding both to JNI wrapper and pure decoderrn - huge speed-up of `DictionaryData` initializationrnrn* Add dictionaryless compressed dictionaryrnrn* Fix `sources.lst`rnrn* Fix `sources.lst` and add a note that `libtool` is also required.rnrn* Update setup.pyrnrn* Fix `EagerStreamTest`rnrn* Fix BUILD filernrn* Add missing `libdivsufsort` dependencyrnrn* Fix unused parameter warning.rn

platform: fix unaligned 64-bit accesses on AArch32 (#699)Ensures that Aarch32 Arm builds with an Armv8 compiler do not setrnBROTLI_64_BITS.rnrnThis scenario is possible with ChromeOS builds, as they may use arntoolchain with the target armv7-cros-gnueabi, but with -march=armv8.rnThis will set __ARM_ARCH to 8 (defining BROTLI_TARGET_ARMV8), but willrnalso set __ARM_32BIT_STATE and not __ARM_64BIT_STATE. Without this,rnillegal 64-bit non-word-aligned reads (LDRD) may be emitted.rnrnAlso fix unaligned 64-bit reads on AArch32 - STRD was still possible tornemit.

Without this,rnillegal 64-bit non-word-aligned reads (LDRD) may be emitted.rnrnAlso fix unaligned 64-bit reads on AArch32 - STRD was still possible tornemit.

Cross compilation support (#709)* build: add cross-compilation support to makernrnSet CROSS_COMPILE when running make to use the selected crossrncompilation toolchain, such as arm-linux-gnueabihf, orrnaarch64-linux-gnu.rnrnTesting requires the presence of qemu - 'qemu-$(ARCH)' will be executed,rnwhere ARCH is the first part of the toolchain triplet.rnrn* build: add cross-compilation support to cmakernrnIf C_COMPILER/CXX_COMPILER/CC/CXX are found to have cross-compilationrntriplets in front of the compiler, then qemu will be used to execute therntests.rnrn* CI: add arm-linux-gnueabihf-gcc builder to TravisrnrnThe version of qemu available in Ubuntu trusty (as provided by Travis)rnappears to have a bug in qemu-aarch64, which leads to the compatibilityrntests failing on some inputs, erroneously rejecting the input asrncorrupt.rnrnOnce Travis supports xenial, we could add an aarch64-gnu-linux-gccrnbuilder as well.rnrn* CI: propagate cmake errors out of .travis.shrnrnSeems like even if cmake fails, the error isn't picked up by Travis.rn

decode: faster huffman code loading on 32-bit Arm (#703)* platform: add macro for using the 'aligned' attributernrn* decode: add accessor macros for HuffmanCode fieldsrnrnAdds a constructor function for building HuffmanCode valuesrnso they can be accessed quickly on different architectures.rnrnAlso adds macros for marking a HuffmanCode table pointerrnthat can be accessed quickly (BROTLI_HC_MARK_TABLE_FOR_FAST_LOAD),rnadjusting the index into that table (BROTLI_HC_ADJUST_TABLE_INDEX),rnand getting the .bits or .value fields out of the table at therncurrent index (BROTLI_HC_GET_BITS/VALUE).rnrnFor example, assuming |table| contains a HuffmanCode pointer:rnrn  BROTLI_HC_MARK_TABLE_FOR_FAST_LOAD(table);rn  BROTLI_HC_ADJUST_TABLE_INDEX(table, index_into_table);rn  *bits = BROTLI_HC_GET_BITS(table);rn  *value = BROTLI_HC_GET_VALUE(table);rn  BROTLI_HC_ADJUST_TABLE_INDEX(table, offset);rn  *bits2 = BROTLI_HC_GET_BITS(table);rn  *value2 = BROTLI_HC_GET_VALUE(table);rnrnAll uses of the HuffmanCode have been updated appropriately.rnrn* decode: add alternative accessors for HuffmanCode on Arm AArch32rn

tools/brotli: improve window size autodetect (#710)Window size is defined as:rn`(1 << BROTLI_PARAM_LGWIN) - 16`rnin `c/include/brotli/encode.h`rnrnTherefore we should probably take these 16 bytes into account.rnrnDone basic manual testing:rn$ python3 -c 'print (A*2046)' > trn$ bazel run -- //:brotli -w 0 -f -o $(realpath t).br $(realpath ./t)rn$ python3 research/brotlidump.py t.br |& fgrep WSIZErn0000  c11000001 WSIZE   windowsize=(1<<12)-16=4080rnrnNew version properly detects window size of `4080`, while previous one used `2032`:rn$ python3 research/brotlidump.py t.br |& fgrep WSIZErn0000  b10110001 WSIZE   windowsize=(1<<11)-16=2032

decode: fix NEON inclusion (#714)The macro that checks for NEON support should be __ARM_NEON, notrn__ARM_NEON__. [1]rnrnAArch64 compilers define __ARM_NEON but not __ARM_NEON__.rnAArch32 compilers currently seem to define both, but could be within theirrnrights to drop __ARM_NEON__ in future versions.rnrnThis change moves the check into the common/platform.h file, checks forrnboth forms, and sets BROTLI_TARGET_NEON if NEON support is available.rnrn[1] Section 6.5.4 of the ARM C Language Extensions.rn(At the time of writing, the latest version was Release 2.1.)
